WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:49.449 --> 00:00:50.449
[music]

00:00:54.067 --> 00:00:57.700
[Peter] Good morning, guys.
Here we are coming into Tybee Island.

00:00:57.700 --> 00:01:00.160
And when most of us
hear of the state of Georgia,

00:01:00.714 --> 00:01:03.214
we don't think of island lifestyle.

00:01:03.444 --> 00:01:05.093
So today we're going to get into it.

00:01:05.093 --> 00:01:08.533
Three different islands.
Tybee, Jekyll, St. Simons.

00:01:09.168 --> 00:01:11.779
We crossed a bridge.
Then we have some marshland.

00:01:11.779 --> 00:01:13.329
Big houses off in the distance.

00:01:13.901 --> 00:01:17.568
So Tybee is about 30 minutes from Savannah.

00:01:18.130 --> 00:01:20.962
This part of Georgia,
if you look at a map, a ton of islands.

00:01:21.206 --> 00:01:23.274
Some completely uninhabited.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:26.309
Others, like Tybee,
people are living obviously.

00:01:26.931 --> 00:01:29.715
Gotta say Tybee streets are pretty quiet.

00:01:30.208 --> 00:01:32.459
No signs of life other than cars.

00:01:33.910 --> 00:01:34.910
[birds chirping]

00:01:35.780 --> 00:01:37.516
[Peter] Let's check this place out.

00:01:40.993 --> 00:01:42.243
[Peter] You already got one?

00:01:42.243 --> 00:01:43.243
Yeah, right here.

00:01:45.446 --> 00:01:46.949
-[giggling]
-Oh, man.

00:01:48.429 --> 00:01:51.331
On Tybee, generally 10:00 AM
is when we start the day.

00:01:51.647 --> 00:01:52.901
-Is it a late morning here?

00:01:52.901 --> 00:01:54.361
It's a very late morning.

00:01:54.854 --> 00:01:57.787
Personally, I do early mornings,
Tuesdays and Thursdays anyhow.

00:01:58.120 --> 00:02:01.543
But for working, I would say the shops
don't really start to open until 10:00.

00:02:02.063 --> 00:02:03.768
So you'll see all of us going to

00:02:03.768 --> 00:02:06.410
the very few coffee shops
that we actually have.

00:02:06.410 --> 00:02:08.984
-And this is one of them, World of Candy?
-Yes.

00:02:10.197 --> 00:02:12.960
-You ain't Tybee.
-You ain't Tybee is what?

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:15.524
You ain't Tybee is a saying

00:02:15.525 --> 00:02:18.056
that was made up by a resident OG local.

00:02:18.056 --> 00:02:19.110
His name is Joel.

00:02:19.110 --> 00:02:21.069
And so he and some of his buddies

00:02:21.070 --> 00:02:23.977
will heckle the tourists
that are driving around.

00:02:24.323 --> 00:02:27.648
And will let you know you are not a local
but they're happy to have you here anyway.

00:02:27.648 --> 00:02:28.879
-You're taking me on the cart?

00:02:28.879 --> 00:02:30.525
-I'm taking you on the cart.
-No way.

00:02:30.525 --> 00:02:32.184
This is your open air limo.

00:02:32.184 --> 00:02:34.920
And I want you to just kind of
look around at the island.

00:02:34.920 --> 00:02:36.524
And this is not to slam Tybee,

00:02:36.911 --> 00:02:39.144
but this is as fancy as we ever got.

00:02:39.535 --> 00:02:41.040
And this is how we like it.

00:02:41.314 --> 00:02:44.405
To be stuck in the past
means you are forced to slow down.

00:02:44.405 --> 00:02:46.129
And that is how the locals want to be.

00:02:46.129 --> 00:02:48.561
We live slow.
We keep the stress levels low.

00:02:48.819 --> 00:02:51.839
And so even if you show up late,
it's Tybee time.

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:53.924
-Tybee is a bit in the '90s.

00:02:53.924 --> 00:02:55.824
Indeed. That's thanks to the Olympics.

00:02:56.185 --> 00:02:58.521
The Olympics wanted to have
their volleyball games here.

00:02:58.521 --> 00:03:02.087
We didn't make the cut. The strip clubs
were a big no-no for the commissions.

00:03:02.087 --> 00:03:04.150
They ended up using us
for the wind and the water.

00:03:04.150 --> 00:03:06.040
-To do Olympics, you need strip clubs?

00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:08.150
No, we had too many strip clubs.

00:03:08.570 --> 00:03:10.343
Although that would have
made a great sport.

00:03:10.343 --> 00:03:11.343
[laughter]

00:03:11.916 --> 00:03:14.830
No, they ended up using us
for the sailboat races only.

00:03:15.102 --> 00:03:18.464
So that brought a little bit.
We had a facelift here in the early '90s

00:03:18.464 --> 00:03:21.148
just trying to appeal
to the Olympic Commission.

00:03:21.609 --> 00:03:24.463
We thought that we could bring
a lot of money to revitalize the island.

00:03:24.463 --> 00:03:28.283
We really fell off the radar
at the end of the '60s during inflation.

00:03:28.575 --> 00:03:30.918
And then from there,
we've kind of taken it over.

00:03:30.918 --> 00:03:32.120
There's just about…

00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:33.400
-Oh, thank you for this.

00:03:33.400 --> 00:03:36.950
Maybe just over 3,000 locals
that actually live on this island.

00:03:37.358 --> 00:03:40.190
So, you know,
the seatbelts are an option here.

00:03:40.550 --> 00:03:44.050
-We aren't popping wheelies on the carts.
-You do have the necker knob.

00:03:44.339 --> 00:03:46.139
Yes, it's a suicide knob right here.

00:03:46.487 --> 00:03:48.959
Just in case we go off-roadin'
which does happen.

00:03:49.429 --> 00:03:50.756
-So this is your job?

00:03:50.756 --> 00:03:52.365
-This is what I do.
-This is what you do.

00:03:52.365 --> 00:03:53.597
-Okay, lucky me.

00:03:53.597 --> 00:03:55.985
-I left the classroom after 15 years
and this is what I do.

00:03:55.985 --> 00:03:57.098
You were a teacher?

00:03:57.098 --> 00:04:00.394
I was a history educator
and professor for 15 years.

00:04:00.394 --> 00:04:03.071
The history teacher in me
wants to automatically wave over here

00:04:03.071 --> 00:04:04.972
at what we call the White House on Tybee.

00:04:04.972 --> 00:04:05.972
-Okay.

00:04:05.973 --> 00:04:08.761
This is an old communications cottage
to a military base

00:04:08.761 --> 00:04:12.086
established here in 1897
for the Spanish-American War.

00:04:12.086 --> 00:04:14.176
-Oh, you know your history here.
-Yes.

00:04:14.176 --> 00:04:16.728
Okay, back to teaching.

00:04:17.102 --> 00:04:19.310
-You quit teaching to do this.
-I did.

00:04:19.492 --> 00:04:20.538
Do you miss teaching?

00:04:20.538 --> 00:04:23.100
 I'm teaching you right now,
you just don't know it.

00:04:23.100 --> 00:04:24.297
There you go.

00:04:24.297 --> 00:04:29.137
We're traditionally a tiny island
with a drinking and surfing problem.

00:04:29.918 --> 00:04:33.877
People would prefer to hit the bars,
hit the beach, and then take a nap.

00:04:34.550 --> 00:04:37.124
And so it's really nice to fit the gap

00:04:37.125 --> 00:04:39.413
of actually sharing
the history of the island.

00:04:39.906 --> 00:04:43.019
I mean, we're passing the old day hospital
and the old morgue there.

00:04:43.019 --> 00:04:45.652
So when we had a fort here,
I don't know if you know anything

00:04:45.652 --> 00:04:47.892
about Spanish-American War.
It didn't even last a year.

00:04:47.892 --> 00:04:49.866
Nothing was finished here at the fort.

00:04:50.281 --> 00:04:54.128
And so they ultimately decided to
turn us into a government party island.

00:04:54.381 --> 00:04:56.812
We started greasing the pockets
of congressional members

00:04:56.812 --> 00:04:58.365
that are coming here on vacation.

00:04:58.365 --> 00:05:00.727
I'm going to take you
to see how those officers lived.

00:05:00.727 --> 00:05:01.727
Oh, cool.

00:05:01.728 --> 00:05:03.579
These are lived in by locals.

00:05:03.579 --> 00:05:05.400
Now, there is one that can be rented.

00:05:05.400 --> 00:05:07.527
It's a bed and breakfast called Surf Song.

00:05:07.527 --> 00:05:10.500
But otherwise,
these houses were all snatched up

00:05:10.740 --> 00:05:13.665
in the early 1960s by a single family.

00:05:13.665 --> 00:05:16.430
We love them, though,
because of the historic preservation.

00:05:16.430 --> 00:05:19.491
Oh, that's great. Look at those oaks.
Those oaks are so beautiful.

00:05:19.491 --> 00:05:21.560
-Those are oaks, right?
-They are live oak trees.

00:05:21.560 --> 00:05:24.029
Live oaks.
Is there such thing as a dead oak?

00:05:24.029 --> 00:05:25.920
-Why do you call them live oaks?
-[giggles]

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:27.170
I mean, dead oak is dead.

00:05:27.633 --> 00:05:29.796
I'm not sure why they get the name live.

00:05:29.796 --> 00:05:31.946
I do know that they have a very dense wood.

00:05:32.245 --> 00:05:36.122
You can tell the density
of the wood based on the size of the leaf.

00:05:36.993 --> 00:05:39.323
We do have an original gazebo.

00:05:39.323 --> 00:05:42.245
So, speaking of party island,
Tybee is still a party island.

00:05:42.245 --> 00:05:43.853
We have open container here.

00:05:43.853 --> 00:05:47.840
So, as long as you are not in
the driver's seat, you can have, not glass…

00:05:47.840 --> 00:05:49.986
What do you got in there?
Do you have some Baileys?

00:05:50.432 --> 00:05:52.640
Listen, if it had Baileys,
you'd be holding it.

00:05:52.640 --> 00:05:55.030
But you can have a drink

00:05:55.031 --> 00:05:57.388
as long as you're not the driver
and it's not in glass.

00:05:57.388 --> 00:05:59.156
So, open container, but imagine,

00:05:59.462 --> 00:06:03.308
most of the cellars that you're going to
see in the sergeants and above,

00:06:03.308 --> 00:06:05.865
with these officers, they have
liquor stills in their basements.

00:06:05.865 --> 00:06:08.855
And then they would use gazebos
like this one to hide from the heat

00:06:08.855 --> 00:06:11.860
while they sipped and enjoyed the band
as they paraded through this area.

00:06:12.215 --> 00:06:15.320
Which is now a coveted HOA on the island.

00:06:15.320 --> 00:06:17.520
This is tourist stuff
or is it second home stuff?

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:18.979
-Second homes.
-Okay.

00:06:18.979 --> 00:06:21.040
-The city has said…
-Look at that contrast.

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:23.820
Uh-huh.
This is a local home as you can understand.

00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:25.079
So, the city has done the math.

00:06:25.079 --> 00:06:28.286
If everybody lived on the island that owned
a home like these secondary homes,

00:06:28.286 --> 00:06:31.566
our population would be
nearly 30,000 residents.

00:06:31.566 --> 00:06:32.566
And it's 3,000.

00:06:32.566 --> 00:06:33.566
-And it's 3,000.
-Okay.

00:06:33.566 --> 00:06:35.873
So, people are just coming here
for a few weeks at a time.

00:06:35.873 --> 00:06:37.820
Some of them do rent out their houses.

00:06:37.820 --> 00:06:41.752
And I encourage people when they come
to Tybee, look at the local rentals.

00:06:41.752 --> 00:06:45.840
Because locals are renting out
their home spaces without that hotel tax.

00:06:45.840 --> 00:06:47.626
-So, that's the old military housing there.

00:06:47.626 --> 00:06:50.296
-Yes, it is.
You see the ghost inside too, right?

00:06:50.296 --> 00:06:53.013
We have all kinds of spirits
here on Tybee Island. [laughs]

00:06:53.013 --> 00:06:54.673
-Is that a thing here?
-It is.

00:06:54.673 --> 00:06:57.662
Is that a Georgia thing? 'Cause in
Savannah, they're talking about it too.

00:06:57.662 --> 00:07:00.886
Savannah is considered to be one of
the most haunted cities in America.

00:07:00.886 --> 00:07:03.862
And I have to agree.
There's lots of spooky apparitions.

00:07:03.862 --> 00:07:06.527
On Tybee,
I would like to say that we're haunted.

00:07:06.527 --> 00:07:09.916
But I do think it's the alcohol spirits
that get the best of us.

00:07:09.916 --> 00:07:12.066
So, these are all the officer's homes.

00:07:12.066 --> 00:07:15.145
And it's a really untapped
part of our history.

00:07:15.145 --> 00:07:17.373
And because they were bought
by private families,

00:07:17.373 --> 00:07:20.275
they have stayed
with their integrity of history.

00:07:20.275 --> 00:07:21.275
-Oh, cool.

00:07:21.275 --> 00:07:23.735
But you can also
stay down here in the history too.

00:07:23.735 --> 00:07:25.600
That's one of the cool things
about the island.

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:28.160
It's a mixture of
both the modern and the old.

00:07:28.513 --> 00:07:31.492
But they're we are
so passionate about our history

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:35.365
that they have made the structures
look very much like the old.

00:07:36.158 --> 00:07:38.567
You would think that
these are a part of the old history.

00:07:38.567 --> 00:07:40.293
They're not.
-They're not, those are new.

00:07:40.293 --> 00:07:42.907
We have a nickname on Tybee.
You may have heard of it.

00:07:42.907 --> 00:07:45.263
We are the Redneck Riviera. [laughs]

00:07:45.263 --> 00:07:47.551
-I knew nothing
about Tybee until two days ago.

00:07:47.551 --> 00:07:50.251
As long as you don't call us Tibby.
We're Tybee Island.

00:07:50.744 --> 00:07:52.232
It's alright.
We're happy to have you.

00:07:52.232 --> 00:07:53.878
So, there's some Redneck spirit out here.

00:07:53.878 --> 00:07:56.192
Oh, we're all.
Yeah. Get out your banjo.

00:07:56.192 --> 00:07:58.466
Matter of fact, there's a little bar,

00:07:58.466 --> 00:08:00.509
Doc's, down on the south end by the pier.

00:08:00.510 --> 00:08:03.297
And they still break out the banjos
every Tuesday night.

00:08:03.297 --> 00:08:06.447
So, open mic, bring your instrument,
and we all get to clapping.

00:08:07.080 --> 00:08:08.962
-Banjos and open container.

00:08:08.962 --> 00:08:10.614
-That's right.
-That's what you want?

00:08:10.614 --> 00:08:12.482
That's what we got. [giggles]

00:08:15.540 --> 00:08:17.519
[Jacqueline] My friend Jenny
is in this last home.

00:08:17.519 --> 00:08:19.212
Her grandmother, Wilma,

00:08:19.213 --> 00:08:21.833
she was a world-renowned architect in 1964,

00:08:22.178 --> 00:08:25.697
bought the first five of these
officer's homes for $5,000 a piece.

00:08:26.006 --> 00:08:27.817
The family still lives in them.

00:08:27.817 --> 00:08:29.901
And so, the really cool thing
in the basement here

00:08:29.901 --> 00:08:33.079
that Jenny has shared
is the remnants of what an interny,

00:08:33.079 --> 00:08:36.039
a Nazi German spy
was held here during World War II.

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:38.863
-You had the U-boats off here.
-We sure did.

00:08:38.863 --> 00:08:42.416
And there were murals
painted all along the walls from that spy

00:08:42.416 --> 00:08:44.582
that was held captive here
and they're still intact.

00:08:44.582 --> 00:08:45.582
Can we get in there?

00:08:46.555 --> 00:08:48.008
-[laughs] Probably not.
-Okay.

00:08:48.610 --> 00:08:50.960
Okay. So, you were saying…
I had the camera off.

00:08:51.874 --> 00:08:53.760
-You've been all over the world.
-Yes.

00:08:53.760 --> 00:08:55.622
Tybee's your final stop, your place.

00:08:55.622 --> 00:08:57.194
It has everything that you could want.

00:08:57.194 --> 00:09:01.023
Not only are you on a small island,
you are required to have community. Right?

00:09:01.397 --> 00:09:03.584
On a small island,
you have to know your neighbors.

00:09:03.584 --> 00:09:08.460
But we also have bodegas, little stores,
at several of the central locations.

00:09:08.460 --> 00:09:12.463
So no matter where you're living,
you just walk to your little bodega.

00:09:12.463 --> 00:09:14.520
It's open until 11:00,
whatever you may need,

00:09:14.521 --> 00:09:16.691
your ice cream or your candies or whatever.

00:09:17.254 --> 00:09:21.451
But we also have
so many reasons to play on the island.

00:09:21.451 --> 00:09:23.897
We have parades
scheduled throughout our year

00:09:23.897 --> 00:09:26.719
and we love when we have
our tourists come out here as well.

00:09:26.719 --> 00:09:28.866
We get about 2 million tourists annually.

00:09:28.866 --> 00:09:31.908
-Oh, it's a big deal out here.
-It's what we're running on.

00:09:31.908 --> 00:09:33.894
-Okay.
-We are based on tourism.

00:09:33.894 --> 00:09:36.116
And we absolutely love our tourists.

00:09:36.116 --> 00:09:38.653
Look at our live oak
becoming an angel over here.

00:09:38.653 --> 00:09:40.385
-What's an angel?
When the branch goes down?

00:09:40.385 --> 00:09:42.482
-That's right.
When the limbs touch the ground.

00:09:42.482 --> 00:09:45.682
They say that the angels
are gracing the ground with their limbs.

00:09:47.906 --> 00:09:52.083
So we're happy to say that
Tybee is a lot of heart and soul

00:09:52.083 --> 00:09:54.430
and because we have just a few locals

00:09:54.431 --> 00:09:57.188
that are making her stay this beautiful,

00:09:57.188 --> 00:09:58.825
so much integrity with her history,

00:09:58.825 --> 00:10:00.673
I feel like we are the ones that are

00:10:00.673 --> 00:10:03.379
keeping her in alignment
with what she's always been.

00:10:03.919 --> 00:10:06.429
You know, Tybee before the 1930s

00:10:06.430 --> 00:10:10.428
had about a 40/60 Black, White population.

00:10:10.428 --> 00:10:12.297
-There was no racial tension.
-Okay.

00:10:12.297 --> 00:10:14.696
It was so challenging
to make this island take off

00:10:14.696 --> 00:10:16.228
that everybody had to work together

00:10:16.228 --> 00:10:19.146
and we still have that same method
of living on the island.

00:10:19.146 --> 00:10:20.396
Everybody works together.

00:10:20.887 --> 00:10:23.739
This was not constructed until after 1898.

00:10:23.990 --> 00:10:27.693
None of it was finished until after the war
that it was established for was over.

00:10:28.360 --> 00:10:30.007
We never used these in battle.

00:10:30.007 --> 00:10:32.469
-Okay. So you're just getting ready
for the next battle.

00:10:32.469 --> 00:10:33.917
So basically Tybee Island,

00:10:33.917 --> 00:10:37.197
while we were intended to
protect the river, the city of Savannah,

00:10:37.775 --> 00:10:39.825
we were a party island, we never had war.

00:10:40.475 --> 00:10:43.125
But there's a fort
between here and Savannah.

00:10:43.125 --> 00:10:45.349
-And that is Fort Pulaski.
-Yeah.

00:10:45.349 --> 00:10:48.814
Fort Pulaski was constructed
out of more than 25 million bricks

00:10:49.069 --> 00:10:52.945
and it was built, I believe,
starting at the end of the 1820s,

00:10:53.227 --> 00:10:56.430
would span, not finishing
until the end of the 1840s.

00:10:56.430 --> 00:10:58.812
And they would use that
during the Civil War.

00:10:58.812 --> 00:10:59.812
But,

00:11:00.391 --> 00:11:02.931
this is the fourth iteration
of the lighthouse.

00:11:02.931 --> 00:11:05.697
The third iteration,
the Confederate soldiers burned down

00:11:05.697 --> 00:11:07.503
when the Union was on their way.

00:11:07.503 --> 00:11:10.125
And the bottom 60 feet
were bricks so it didn't burn.

00:11:10.125 --> 00:11:14.063
The Union used that as their staging to put
the rifle cannons and launch their attack.

00:11:14.063 --> 00:11:16.377
And that's when
they blew the hole open on that fort.

00:11:16.377 --> 00:11:18.143
-What year did the Union get control here?

00:11:18.143 --> 00:11:20.518
It was Spring, April, of 1862.

00:11:21.298 --> 00:11:23.863
-Wow. I met the right person.
You know all the dates.

00:11:23.863 --> 00:11:25.020
All of the things.

00:11:25.020 --> 00:11:28.311
And so ultimately you may see a sign
when you come on and off the island.

00:11:28.311 --> 00:11:32.320
This is to pay homage to the mistreatment
of the Confederates of that Fort Pulaski.

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:35.619
We turned it into a prisoners of war camp
and we starved them out.

00:11:35.619 --> 00:11:37.310
Only 13 of the men starved to death.

00:11:37.310 --> 00:11:41.880
So we named that section of highway
the Immortal 600 Soldiers Memorial Highway.

00:11:42.167 --> 00:11:45.430
You will see that sign and you will go, ah,
whenever you come back to the island.

00:11:45.430 --> 00:11:48.373
Okay. So in Northern education,
Northeastern education,

00:11:48.373 --> 00:11:52.123
perhaps it was, you know, everything
bad Confederate, everything good Union.

00:11:52.424 --> 00:11:55.140
-The narrative. The basic narrative.
-That was the narrative.

00:11:55.140 --> 00:11:58.938
Unless you're in the South, it's the,
you know, the War Between States.

00:11:58.938 --> 00:12:02.010
And they say the South won,
which we know is not the case.

00:12:02.010 --> 00:12:05.505
Now that the history is behind us,
it's maybe not so much important

00:12:05.505 --> 00:12:08.755
to say what is good or what is bad,
but what we should not repeat.

00:12:09.336 --> 00:12:10.936
-That's a good way of saying it.

00:12:12.470 --> 00:12:15.595
[woman] It's easy to tap into nature.
It's easy to drop your phone.

00:12:15.595 --> 00:12:16.947
You don't even bring it with you.

00:12:16.947 --> 00:12:20.597
You're going for a walk and you enter
that realm of timelessness on Tybee.

00:12:21.025 --> 00:12:23.726
And the locals, we are the ones
that are choosing not to have

00:12:23.726 --> 00:12:26.480
the high-rises,
not to have the corporations come in.

00:12:26.480 --> 00:12:28.390
Right. I noticed that, no high-rises.

00:12:28.733 --> 00:12:29.760
35 feet.

00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:31.716
-That's the height variation.
-Okay.

00:12:31.716 --> 00:12:32.690
The variance.

00:12:32.690 --> 00:12:34.086
What's rent like here?

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:36.000
[sighs]

00:12:36.939 --> 00:12:39.200
We're going negative now.
I finally got you on something.

00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:42.198
Luckily, I am a homeowner, but we,

00:12:42.198 --> 00:12:46.067
for someone who needs employees,
it's hard to find affordable housing.

00:12:46.067 --> 00:12:49.224
However, if people are coming
and they're renting,

00:12:49.224 --> 00:12:53.073
there are several businesses that are
family-owned that have bought houses

00:12:53.294 --> 00:12:55.919
and have turned them into
affordable housing for employment.

00:12:56.443 --> 00:12:59.602
-Okay, but it's a tight housing market?
-Very tight.

00:12:59.602 --> 00:13:01.302
We're on an island, not many homes.

00:13:01.302 --> 00:13:05.579
You're not going to find a studio
probably under $1,500 here.

00:13:05.579 --> 00:13:08.882
Like 400 square…
it's New York, California.

00:13:09.231 --> 00:13:12.966
-It's a bit lower, but that's…
-Yeah, we call it New York and California.

00:13:12.966 --> 00:13:14.766
'Cause we're not used to it.

00:13:14.767 --> 00:13:19.039
Back in 2015, you saw one bedroom,
one and a half bathrooms

00:13:19.040 --> 00:13:20.323
for 700 bucks.

00:13:20.777 --> 00:13:24.171
So just in a decade, this has over doubled.

00:13:25.110 --> 00:13:26.716
-Look at this.
-Isn't this amazing?

00:13:26.716 --> 00:13:28.288
Jacqueline, I had no idea.

00:13:28.288 --> 00:13:31.829
I never thought of Georgian islands
or Georgian beaches.

00:13:31.829 --> 00:13:35.416
Me being in my own world and not being
in this part of the country enough.

00:13:35.416 --> 00:13:37.157
We're at the beginning of the Golden Isles.

00:13:37.157 --> 00:13:39.798
I think that we're often overlooked
because of how small we are.

00:13:39.799 --> 00:13:42.499
You know, just some 15 miles
off the coast of Savannah.

00:13:43.150 --> 00:13:45.549
But we have it all.
We have a beautiful beach.

00:13:45.549 --> 00:13:46.784
We have a surf break.

00:13:46.785 --> 00:13:51.683
So where these jetties are, an old
installation to prevent sand erosion.

00:13:51.941 --> 00:13:56.389
When the waters fill in
at high tide now, this is where we surf.

00:13:56.865 --> 00:13:59.160
When it's low tide like this,
on a less windy day,

00:13:59.160 --> 00:14:01.629
you're going to see
all of the fishermen lined up here

00:14:01.630 --> 00:14:03.448
doing their fishing scene and things.

00:14:03.448 --> 00:14:05.280
-This is nice sand.
-It's great sand.

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:08.163
I mean this is wet.
We're at low tide, but…

00:14:08.163 --> 00:14:11.184
-You can see the wrack line.
So high tide is going to come up to here.

00:14:11.184 --> 00:14:13.790
-Yeah.
-We're fabulous for shark tooth hunting.

00:14:14.020 --> 00:14:17.147
Because of the river's exit
right here at the Savannah River,

00:14:17.147 --> 00:14:18.736
you know, the little bull sharks,

00:14:18.736 --> 00:14:22.708
they're born with about 50 rows of teeth
and they litter their teeth on our shores.

00:14:22.709 --> 00:14:24.554
-So we have awesome shark tooth hunting.
-Okay.

00:14:24.554 --> 00:14:26.573
They're about to do
something that the locals love.

00:14:26.573 --> 00:14:28.240
It's called a low tide ride.

00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:30.978
So at low tide, you time it,
you bring out your beach cruiser,

00:14:30.978 --> 00:14:33.568
and that's that timelessness element
of Tybee,

00:14:33.568 --> 00:14:34.883
where you just ride your bike.

00:14:34.883 --> 00:14:37.597
You're not touching your phone,
you're watching the beach,

00:14:37.597 --> 00:14:40.369
you're watching the birds,
you're watching the dunes,

00:14:40.369 --> 00:14:41.603
and you're just enjoying life.

00:14:41.603 --> 00:14:44.688
Is this, summertime,
would this be crowded or not really?

00:14:44.949 --> 00:14:46.291
Completely crowded.

00:14:46.549 --> 00:14:50.936
There's a few sections of the island
and the beaches that the locals know to go,

00:14:50.936 --> 00:14:54.684
but this area right here
is called the local's beach.

00:14:54.970 --> 00:14:58.056
So this is North Beach
and past the jetty line

00:14:58.463 --> 00:15:01.649
all the way up toward the river, this is
where the locals are going to set up

00:15:01.649 --> 00:15:03.615
and we have our own
little private section here.

00:15:03.615 --> 00:15:06.940
The reason why the tourists
are not as inclined to go that direction

00:15:06.940 --> 00:15:09.359
is it's further away
from the restroom and a restaurant.

00:15:10.924 --> 00:15:12.417
[Jacqueline] How precious is that?

00:15:12.417 --> 00:15:14.559
-Yeah, that's what you want.
-You're a kid again.

00:15:14.559 --> 00:15:17.280
[Peter] I mean, they got the screens,
but they're just taking photos.

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:19.497
Gotta remember it.
Look it, they're having a great time.

00:15:19.497 --> 00:15:23.281
-She said, I love it. Yes, you do.
You get to be a child again on this island.

00:15:26.763 --> 00:15:28.274
[Jacqueline] That's Hilton Head.

00:15:28.274 --> 00:15:30.469
-Okay, that's famous, Hilton Head?
-Yes.

00:15:30.469 --> 00:15:32.628
-That's South Carolina.
Super wealthy, right?

00:15:32.628 --> 00:15:34.711
Very wealthy. Of course, it's corporate,

00:15:34.711 --> 00:15:38.598
and it's a maritime forest
rather than a sand barrier island.

00:15:38.599 --> 00:15:41.667
-Okay, so I'm going to Jekyll today.
-Cool.

00:15:41.667 --> 00:15:43.381
-And St. Simons.
-Oh, yes.

00:15:43.381 --> 00:15:46.246
And the goal of the video
is to show three different islands,

00:15:46.246 --> 00:15:48.670
three different existences for the locals.

00:15:48.670 --> 00:15:50.595
-'Cause they all have different vibes?
-Yes.

00:15:50.595 --> 00:15:53.670
Jekyll is great. You're gonna see
some of the history there.

00:15:53.670 --> 00:15:57.640
But I will say, as you keep going south
it's like bigger money, bigger money.

00:15:57.640 --> 00:16:00.290
And as soon as you cross to the island,
you gotta pay.

00:16:00.919 --> 00:16:03.582
-Are you serious?
-Uh-huh. You gotta pay to cross the bridge.

00:16:03.582 --> 00:16:06.589
-I didn't know that.
-Yeah, I think it's like a $10 fee.

00:16:07.035 --> 00:16:10.385
And Tybee is not that, right?
We joke and say we're Redneck Riviera,

00:16:10.861 --> 00:16:14.801
but the locals do not want
to stop people from coming here.

00:16:14.801 --> 00:16:16.521
It should not be about cost.

00:16:16.835 --> 00:16:19.080
It should be about,
do you want to go to the beach?

00:16:19.080 --> 00:16:22.107
And do you want to relax
and be able to check out of the world

00:16:22.107 --> 00:16:23.991
that you are wanting an escape from?

00:16:24.265 --> 00:16:25.334
We offer that.

00:16:25.335 --> 00:16:29.285
We're not having you roll down your window
at the bridge and give a credit card.

00:16:30.519 --> 00:16:32.690
This is an old fortress

00:16:32.691 --> 00:16:37.443
and a really great example of how
Tybee has let its history continue to be

00:16:37.443 --> 00:16:39.962
without adapting, manipulating to modern.

00:16:40.388 --> 00:16:42.307
And so this is old Battery Habersham.

00:16:42.307 --> 00:16:43.357
This is all original.

00:16:46.950 --> 00:16:49.825
There's a fortress poured
to face the North Savannah River.

00:16:49.825 --> 00:16:51.620
It was finished in the year 1900.

00:16:51.620 --> 00:16:55.251
And keep in mind, we didn't even have
but 200, maybe 250 enlisted men

00:16:55.252 --> 00:16:57.040
that managed the entire fort.

00:16:57.666 --> 00:16:59.162
So it was a very low numbers,

00:16:59.162 --> 00:17:02.065
a very non-intrusive fort by any means.

00:17:02.315 --> 00:17:05.071
It was, of course,
bolstering with the tourism.

00:17:05.071 --> 00:17:07.909
So these enlisted men
who did not have to worry about war

00:17:07.909 --> 00:17:10.368
were really worried about going
to the south end of the island

00:17:10.368 --> 00:17:12.096
to find a girlfriend on vacation.

00:17:12.980 --> 00:17:14.880
Could you imagine
being stationed here?

00:17:15.245 --> 00:17:17.310
No war.
You're not really worried about anything.

00:17:17.310 --> 00:17:19.869
You just got to walk the beach
down about a mile and a half

00:17:19.869 --> 00:17:22.180
and that's where all
the parties are happening.

00:17:22.180 --> 00:17:23.750
It's a good place to live.

00:17:27.686 --> 00:17:30.365
[Peter] So it's all behind here.
The fortress is still there.

00:17:30.365 --> 00:17:33.783
[Jacqueline] And it's not developed.
It's untapped. The city still owns it.

00:17:33.850 --> 00:17:35.961
And it faces our police department
on the other side.

00:17:35.961 --> 00:17:38.014
It's a one-stop shop here. It's Mayberry.

00:17:38.014 --> 00:17:39.566
-That's a nice police department.

00:17:39.566 --> 00:17:41.786
-Jail, offices, and courthouse.

00:17:41.786 --> 00:17:43.693
-I've never seen a jail look so nice.

00:17:43.693 --> 00:17:44.960
-With rocking chairs.

00:17:44.960 --> 00:17:48.978
-Right. It looks like a nice restaurant
and a place to get married, maybe.

00:17:50.240 --> 00:17:52.417
Jacqueline, I got lucky meeting you.

00:17:52.417 --> 00:17:53.957
-So thank you.
-It's an honor, Peter.

00:17:53.957 --> 00:17:56.938
I wouldn't have seen any of that.
And I got a lot of ground to cover today.

00:17:56.938 --> 00:17:59.401
-Yeah.
-But I do want to tell people what you do.

00:17:59.791 --> 00:18:01.981
-And you do this, right?
-I do this. Yeah.

00:18:01.982 --> 00:18:04.546
We operate the tours on the island.

00:18:04.546 --> 00:18:06.899
Tybee Tour Company. We're easy to find.

00:18:07.220 --> 00:18:09.750
Okay. I'm going to leave your link
because you're awesome.

00:18:09.750 --> 00:18:11.928
Thank you. Bring your family
next time y'all come back.

00:18:11.928 --> 00:18:13.701
Call me directly and I'll hook y'all up.

00:18:13.701 --> 00:18:15.793
-So here's the Tybee Tour Company.

00:18:15.793 --> 00:18:18.840
-It is easy to find us.
I'm the only tour company on the island.

00:18:18.840 --> 00:18:21.263
-Are you serious?
-Everything else is on the water.

00:18:21.330 --> 00:18:22.330
[country music]

00:18:35.558 --> 00:18:39.165
All right, guys. We're back on the mainland
in a town called Darien.

00:18:39.511 --> 00:18:41.798
We're going to get on
to Jekyll Island soon.

00:18:41.798 --> 00:18:45.001
But I just want to check out
this cool little town here

00:18:45.355 --> 00:18:47.114
with these beautiful circles.

00:18:47.114 --> 00:18:48.830
Never seen anything like it.

00:18:48.830 --> 00:18:52.446
The road just
wraps around these little parks.

00:18:53.780 --> 00:18:55.180
These streets are beautiful.

00:18:55.994 --> 00:18:57.420
Slow living out here.

00:18:58.470 --> 00:19:00.930
The sound that the Spanish moss makes.

00:19:01.133 --> 00:19:05.073
Very soothing.
Sort of like the winds in a cornfield or

00:19:05.453 --> 00:19:07.632
tall grass, ocean waves.

00:19:08.145 --> 00:19:09.995
Sort of that melodic effect going on.

00:19:12.990 --> 00:19:14.237
How you doing, ma'am?

00:19:14.540 --> 00:19:17.323
-Your trees are amazing.
-Aren't they wonderful?

00:19:17.390 --> 00:19:18.702
What's Darien known for?

00:19:19.409 --> 00:19:21.948
-Shrimping.
-Shrimping. Is that still happening?

00:19:22.290 --> 00:19:23.796
-Mm-hmm.
-It's still going on?

00:19:23.796 --> 00:19:25.108
-Oh yeah.
-Great.

00:19:25.351 --> 00:19:26.644
So they're fishermen here?

00:19:26.644 --> 00:19:29.335
If you go to the waterfront,
you'll be able to see the shrimp boats.

00:19:29.335 --> 00:19:30.639
-Okay, great.
-Okay.

00:19:30.639 --> 00:19:31.939
Thank you. You're welcome.

00:19:33.263 --> 00:19:38.343
So we'll cruise down to the waterfront
and then get out to Jekyll Island.

00:19:39.042 --> 00:19:42.488
Many of you have heard of Jekyll Island
from the famous book,

00:19:42.488 --> 00:19:44.745
The Creature from Jekyll Island

00:19:45.305 --> 00:19:49.421
and the story of how
the Federal Reserve was started.

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:52.249
It's a nice little downtown here in Darien.

00:20:00.126 --> 00:20:01.126
[men chattering]

00:20:02.612 --> 00:20:05.166
-He was on the TV show.
-He was on there, too.

00:20:05.166 --> 00:20:08.740
[Peter] I do a channel. He actually
watches my stuff, but all over the country.

00:20:08.740 --> 00:20:11.249
Get it from the locals.
What's fishing like right now?

00:20:11.249 --> 00:20:14.821
Right now we're working on boats.
We're doing all our maintenance.

00:20:14.821 --> 00:20:16.454
This is our maintenance time of year.

00:20:16.454 --> 00:20:18.371
-You've always done fishing?
-Yes, sir.

00:20:18.371 --> 00:20:20.170
How is it? Is it a good career?

00:20:20.170 --> 00:20:22.250
-Yeah, fourth generation or fifth.
-Fourth?

00:20:22.250 --> 00:20:24.487
-Yeah,
that's my little brother right there.

00:20:24.487 --> 00:20:26.002
-How old are you?
-37.

00:20:26.508 --> 00:20:28.958
Okay, so the young guys
are still getting into it.

00:20:29.534 --> 00:20:33.128
I don't know about that.
I've been doing it since I was like 10.

00:20:33.768 --> 00:20:35.763
I started running the boat when I was 15.

00:20:36.187 --> 00:20:37.434
-What's your name?
-Michael.

00:20:37.434 --> 00:20:40.740
Michael. Peter.
So what's it like economically these days?

00:20:40.740 --> 00:20:45.122
It's kind of rough. These tariffs
they put on some of our imported seafood,

00:20:45.122 --> 00:20:47.522
it's helped us a little bit
this past year or so.

00:20:47.843 --> 00:20:50.411
And the fuel price
has come down a little bit, but…

00:20:50.411 --> 00:20:53.799
-So, okay, the tariffs
have hurt global competition a little bit.

00:20:53.799 --> 00:20:55.905
-Made it better for you guys?
-Made it better for us.

00:20:55.905 --> 00:20:57.519
-Okay, I didn't even think of that.
-Yep.

00:20:57.519 --> 00:21:00.492
And to be honest, you don't know
what you're eating with them anyway.

00:21:00.492 --> 00:21:02.022
Like them imported shrimp.

00:21:02.022 --> 00:21:03.322
-So you're going out here…

00:21:03.700 --> 00:21:06.472
We go from here to North Carolina,
all the way down to Cape Canaveral.

00:21:06.472 --> 00:21:07.870
-Is there an adventure to it?

00:21:07.870 --> 00:21:09.750
Used to be. Now it's a job.

00:21:10.440 --> 00:21:11.985
Yeah, I'm the youngest of the bunch.

00:21:11.985 --> 00:21:13.582
-How old are you?
-21.

00:21:13.582 --> 00:21:15.010
Nice. Do you like it?

00:21:15.010 --> 00:21:18.110
Oh yeah, it's great.
But I ain't done it long enough, I reckon.

00:21:18.523 --> 00:21:20.855
It's just like anything else, man.
It's hunting, looking,

00:21:20.855 --> 00:21:23.220
and looking, and looking,
and when it's good, it's good.

00:21:23.220 --> 00:21:25.763
It's a freezer boat,
so we freeze everything on here.

00:21:25.763 --> 00:21:27.450
They go into a brine tank.

00:21:27.450 --> 00:21:28.450
-Okay.

00:21:28.450 --> 00:21:32.496
We get it down to about five below zero,
so it freezes them quick.

00:21:33.055 --> 00:21:36.190
And then we put them in the hull
and the hull stays four below.

00:21:36.190 --> 00:21:39.416
If I want to buy Georgian shrimp,
American shrimp,

00:21:39.416 --> 00:21:41.385
how do I know when I'm at a restaurant?

00:21:41.385 --> 00:21:42.385
Ask.

00:21:42.385 --> 00:21:43.705
-You gotta ask?
-You gotta ask.

00:21:43.710 --> 00:21:49.009
I think Georgia just passed a law
that they have to put it on their menu

00:21:49.835 --> 00:21:51.118
to where they come from.

00:21:51.118 --> 00:21:53.344
-That's great. This is totally wild caught?

00:21:53.344 --> 00:21:54.613
100% wild caught.

00:21:54.613 --> 00:21:57.955
-Do your shrimp go all over the country?
Yeah, they go all over.

00:21:57.955 --> 00:22:00.000
One of the biggest issues
that we run into is

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:02.918
having a processing plant
that can package them

00:22:02.918 --> 00:22:05.848
just like the imported shrimp
because they're so convenient.

00:22:05.848 --> 00:22:09.610
They're peeled, deveined,
and sometimes already cooked.

00:22:09.610 --> 00:22:14.889
You can buy them when they're imported,
and they're all uniform size and it's just…

00:22:14.890 --> 00:22:17.300
-It's because they're farmed?
-Yeah, that's right.

00:22:17.300 --> 00:22:19.656
This whole entire waterfront
used to be boats.

00:22:19.656 --> 00:22:20.828
-Down to you guys now?

00:22:20.828 --> 00:22:22.897
Now it's just this one, yep.

00:22:22.897 --> 00:22:24.250
-How many guys are you out here?

00:22:24.250 --> 00:22:26.319
I think every boat's here at the moment.

00:22:26.325 --> 00:22:28.119
-That's it. Okay, that's what's going on.

00:22:28.119 --> 00:22:30.499
Three, six, nine. Nine to ten.

00:22:31.039 --> 00:22:32.943
Thank you for what you do,
'cause I love shrimp.

00:22:32.943 --> 00:22:34.013
Yeah, man.

00:22:34.013 --> 00:22:36.159
Anytime you're around,
and if these boats are working,

00:22:36.159 --> 00:22:37.733
you can buy all you want from here.

00:22:37.733 --> 00:22:38.799
-Really?
-Yeah.

00:22:38.799 --> 00:22:40.460
-Is that for everyone?
-For everyone.

00:22:40.460 --> 00:22:42.102
When it's peak fishing season

00:22:42.380 --> 00:22:44.350
people can come to Darien
and buy from you guys?

00:22:44.350 --> 00:22:45.350
-Yeah.
-All right.

00:22:45.350 --> 00:22:48.043
They can pull up,
and this is going to be a little different,

00:22:48.043 --> 00:22:50.407
but we don't keep anything here.
It's all fresh.

00:22:50.407 --> 00:22:53.335
It comes right off the boat, and then
goes straight to a processing plant.

00:22:53.335 --> 00:22:56.173
But if you're here while we're unloading,
you can buy all you want.

00:22:56.240 --> 00:22:57.320
[boat engine hums]

00:23:09.415 --> 00:23:10.882
[Peter] So you're shrimp king?

00:23:10.882 --> 00:23:13.392
-I don't know about that.
-That's what he said.

00:23:13.392 --> 00:23:14.371
It's skill out there…

00:23:14.371 --> 00:23:17.455
It's go around and mention Ricky Boone.
See what everybody tells you.

00:23:17.455 --> 00:23:19.155
-Ricky Boone?
-Little Ricky Boone.

00:23:19.155 --> 00:23:20.590
Little Ricky. He's Little Ricky?

00:23:20.590 --> 00:23:23.540
-That's Little Ricky. That's his daddy.
-He's not so little.

00:23:23.940 --> 00:23:25.740
-What's your name?
-James Lee.

00:23:25.740 --> 00:23:29.010
This is what it's like? So you guys
are living for how long out here?

00:23:29.010 --> 00:23:32.173
You can stay on this boat up to…
I mean, some people stay out a month.

00:23:32.729 --> 00:23:35.154
We typically stay out
about two weeks or so.

00:23:35.621 --> 00:23:36.621
-Okay.

00:23:36.990 --> 00:23:38.421
Just you and how many guys?

00:23:38.650 --> 00:23:39.910
About four guys.

00:23:39.910 --> 00:23:41.287
So you got two beds here.

00:23:41.850 --> 00:23:43.233
And this way you got…

00:23:44.160 --> 00:23:45.740
There's three beds in there.

00:23:45.740 --> 00:23:47.780
Bigger bed for the captain.

00:23:47.780 --> 00:23:48.930
More of a full size bed.

00:23:48.931 --> 00:23:50.695
-This is the captain's bed?
-Yeah.

00:23:50.695 --> 00:23:51.920
-The separate one.
-Yeah.

00:23:51.920 --> 00:23:54.148
And then you got a…
Just a little bathroom.

00:23:54.148 --> 00:23:55.148
-Okay.

00:23:57.610 --> 00:24:01.060
And then you got a kitchen that's dirty
'cause we're working on the boats now.

00:24:01.060 --> 00:24:02.744
-This is maintenance time.
-Yeah.

00:24:03.912 --> 00:24:06.549
-Full kitchen.
-Yeah, stove and whatever.

00:24:07.166 --> 00:24:08.166
Oh, that's awesome.

00:24:11.299 --> 00:24:12.988
This is where you drive, whatever.

00:24:12.988 --> 00:24:16.386
Pretty basic, radar,
depth finder, all that type of stuff.

00:24:16.890 --> 00:24:19.401
We work 10 months out of the year together.

00:24:20.171 --> 00:24:22.458
Two weeks, come home, take a day or two.

00:24:22.458 --> 00:24:24.824
Sometimes three days off.
Go back another two weeks.

00:24:25.360 --> 00:24:26.901
-So it's like a strong brotherhood?

00:24:26.901 --> 00:24:28.358
Yeah. Basically, yeah.

00:24:28.358 --> 00:24:29.655
-Are you married?
-Yes.

00:24:29.964 --> 00:24:32.021
Is that tough on that? To be away?

00:24:32.021 --> 00:24:33.707
It can be. Yeah, it can be.

00:24:33.707 --> 00:24:36.656
But it's something you got to put up with
if you want to do this, I guess.

00:24:36.656 --> 00:24:38.155
-Yeah. It's your income.

00:24:38.155 --> 00:24:39.613
Yeah. It's good money and…

00:24:39.957 --> 00:24:41.006
-That's cool.

00:24:41.007 --> 00:24:42.466
-It is good money?
-Yeah.

00:24:42.466 --> 00:24:43.820
Sometimes it's not.

00:24:43.820 --> 00:24:45.305
Most of the time, it is.

00:24:45.621 --> 00:24:48.667
It just depends on
how the shrimp prices, fuel prices.

00:24:48.667 --> 00:24:49.667
-Okay.

00:24:50.372 --> 00:24:51.118
Right.

00:24:51.118 --> 00:24:53.303
How everything's going
in the world, basically.

00:24:53.951 --> 00:24:56.200
-Gotcha. Well, thanks for showing me this.

00:24:56.200 --> 00:24:57.200
-Yes, sir.

00:24:58.184 --> 00:24:59.810
And then down here, it's just…

00:24:59.810 --> 00:25:02.245
Don't have lights
since the breaker's tripped, lights is off.

00:25:02.245 --> 00:25:04.690
But there's two engines,
two big main engines down there,

00:25:04.691 --> 00:25:05.994
and two generators down there.

00:25:05.994 --> 00:25:06.994
-Okay.

00:25:08.685 --> 00:25:10.949
It's got to be cool being out on sea,
though, too, right?

00:25:10.949 --> 00:25:13.102
Yeah. You get sunsets every day.

00:25:13.102 --> 00:25:14.670
Sunrise, sunset. It's beautiful.

00:25:15.156 --> 00:25:17.610
-You sort of tap out
from the world a little bit, right?

00:25:17.610 --> 00:25:18.577
Yeah.

00:25:18.577 --> 00:25:21.241
But we got Starlink,
so our phones and everything work.

00:25:21.241 --> 00:25:23.009
-Did that change a lot
when you got Starlink?

00:25:23.009 --> 00:25:26.794
Yeah. Because there's some islands,
like Sapelo Island, you get there,

00:25:26.794 --> 00:25:29.411
before Starlink,
your phone wouldn't work at all.

00:25:29.411 --> 00:25:32.271
No matter if you had Verizon, T-Mobile,
your phone wouldn't work.

00:25:32.271 --> 00:25:34.050
You just read books or something?

00:25:34.050 --> 00:25:36.501
You just sit there
and stare out the window, I guess.

00:25:36.501 --> 00:25:38.833
I don't know.
There wasn't a whole lot to do.

00:25:38.900 --> 00:25:39.900
[country music]

00:25:53.760 --> 00:25:57.799
I believe these are the old gates
to the island that was exclusive.

00:25:58.296 --> 00:26:00.604
No one could enter back in the day.

00:26:00.604 --> 00:26:01.949
It was a private club.

00:26:01.949 --> 00:26:04.346
Morgan, Rockefeller, Vanderbilt.

00:26:04.346 --> 00:26:06.885
A lot of the big wealth of the Gilded Age.

00:26:07.170 --> 00:26:10.170
This was their retreat and it was also,
we're going to get into it,

00:26:10.170 --> 00:26:13.116
where the Federal Reserve started.

00:26:13.710 --> 00:26:15.648
The most powerful bankers in the country

00:26:15.647 --> 00:26:18.567
started the system that we still use today.

00:26:19.080 --> 00:26:20.080
[music continues]

00:26:26.286 --> 00:26:28.359
So in a way, it's still private.

00:26:28.360 --> 00:26:30.307
As in, you need to pay to enter.

00:26:30.550 --> 00:26:32.138
At least you can enter now.

00:26:32.138 --> 00:26:34.623
$10, they say it's a parking fee.

00:26:35.418 --> 00:26:36.393
We're in.

00:26:36.460 --> 00:26:37.460
[music continues]

00:26:53.906 --> 00:26:55.361
Got a game of croquet here.

00:26:55.751 --> 00:26:57.051
The all-White team is out.

00:26:58.338 --> 00:26:59.362
First impressions,

00:26:59.944 --> 00:27:02.333
this place feels like old money.

00:27:02.923 --> 00:27:04.706
Nothing that comes as any surprise.

00:27:05.904 --> 00:27:07.404
There's a ton of history here.

00:27:07.932 --> 00:27:09.801
This is Indian Mound Cottage.

00:27:09.801 --> 00:27:12.388
Apparently there was
a shell mound up front.

00:27:12.705 --> 00:27:15.188
It was Rockefeller's winter residence.

00:27:15.811 --> 00:27:18.193
Look, these homes aren't insanely massive

00:27:19.251 --> 00:27:20.501
for the amount of wealth,

00:27:21.412 --> 00:27:23.229
but they are beautiful.

00:27:31.826 --> 00:27:32.826
[lock clanks]

00:27:32.826 --> 00:27:35.340
Okay.
I think they're all going to be locked.

00:27:38.620 --> 00:27:41.089
All right, guys. If there's
a big hole in the video right now,

00:27:41.089 --> 00:27:44.052
that is because
I had to remove a huge chunk

00:27:44.886 --> 00:27:46.519
here at the Jekyll Island Resort.

00:27:46.887 --> 00:27:48.875
They are very tight.

00:27:49.233 --> 00:27:50.545
Like, very tight.

00:27:50.863 --> 00:27:52.679
Even tried to film
a little bit in the museum.

00:27:52.679 --> 00:27:55.134
They didn't want it.
I've been trying to meet up with someone.

00:27:55.700 --> 00:27:57.648
that knows the history here well.

00:27:57.648 --> 00:28:01.311
You got to go through marketing,
and then you got to go through

00:28:01.311 --> 00:28:02.810
all sorts of departments.

00:28:02.810 --> 00:28:04.575
Unfortunately, it's fallen through.

00:28:04.575 --> 00:28:05.803
I got a bike.

00:28:05.803 --> 00:28:08.262
I can show you some of the homes from afar.

00:28:08.262 --> 00:28:10.108
I can talk a little bit about them.

00:28:10.915 --> 00:28:12.520
That's the next best thing.

00:28:12.520 --> 00:28:13.691
So we're going to cruise.

00:28:13.692 --> 00:28:15.658
We're going to go to some of these homes

00:28:15.658 --> 00:28:18.272
and just show the grounds,
the beauty of it all.

00:28:19.309 --> 00:28:22.231
Just imagine,
not that long ago, the world's elite

00:28:22.915 --> 00:28:24.809
coming to the island in

00:28:25.420 --> 00:28:27.697
seclusion when it came
to the Federal Reserve

00:28:27.697 --> 00:28:29.577
but well, for the most part,

00:28:30.675 --> 00:28:32.007
in seclusion because

00:28:32.693 --> 00:28:35.899
this island was reserved for them.

00:28:36.560 --> 00:28:37.560
Private world.

00:28:39.487 --> 00:28:41.387
Sir, do you know whose house this was?

00:28:42.020 --> 00:28:43.433
[man] William Struthers.

00:28:43.434 --> 00:28:44.589
[Peter] Okay, thank you.

00:28:44.589 --> 00:28:46.469
[man 2] Later it was George Macy.

00:28:46.469 --> 00:28:48.952
[Peter] George Macy. A tea importer.

00:28:51.699 --> 00:28:53.799
[Peter] Here we have the Goodyear cottage.

00:28:54.200 --> 00:28:56.189
I'm guessing Goodyear tires.

00:28:56.917 --> 00:28:58.232
That's a beauty.

00:29:00.856 --> 00:29:03.408
"With only drive and ambition,
Frank Henry Goodyear

00:29:03.409 --> 00:29:05.377
rose from a $35 a month bookkeeper

00:29:05.784 --> 00:29:09.778
to the head of a vast
lumber, coal, iron, and railroad empire."

00:29:10.317 --> 00:29:11.828
So not tires. Different Goodyear.

00:29:12.841 --> 00:29:16.465
Goodyear began his career with
a hundred dollars, a keen business mind,

00:29:16.465 --> 00:29:18.929
and an all-consuming drive to prosper.

00:29:19.275 --> 00:29:23.846
He left his heirs
with a $10 million estate.

00:29:24.530 --> 00:29:25.530
[birds chirping]

00:29:29.547 --> 00:29:30.765
We've got the pool.

00:29:31.578 --> 00:29:32.765
A bit cold for that.

00:29:33.832 --> 00:29:35.317
All the rooms back here.

00:29:37.180 --> 00:29:39.538
Just pathways everywhere like this.

00:29:40.081 --> 00:29:43.408
So you can do a tour here
in those trolley carts.

00:29:43.408 --> 00:29:45.650
They cruise you around, give you a tour,

00:29:45.650 --> 00:29:48.052
but we unfortunately
don't have time for that.

00:29:48.424 --> 00:29:49.809
Crane Cottage.

00:29:49.810 --> 00:29:53.614
The most expensive cottage
on the island at the time it was built.

00:29:53.895 --> 00:29:55.510
I believe you can stay here now.

00:29:55.511 --> 00:29:57.316
There are 13 rooms.

00:29:58.300 --> 00:30:01.081
Crane, the plumbing
and hardware manufacturers.

00:30:01.413 --> 00:30:06.153
It's proof that big money
often comes from not so fancy ideas.

00:30:08.168 --> 00:30:10.621
"Cherokee Cottage, Edwin Gold,

00:30:10.622 --> 00:30:13.314
son of railroad magnate
and financer, J. Gold.

00:30:13.648 --> 00:30:15.618
Owned several properties on Jekyll Island.

00:30:15.958 --> 00:30:19.020
In 1904
he built this cottage for his in-laws.

00:30:19.663 --> 00:30:24.884
In retirement Dr. James devoted himself
to the affairs of the Jekyll Island Club."

00:30:26.024 --> 00:30:27.675
Just think of the back of the day.

00:30:27.675 --> 00:30:28.766
All this wealth here,

00:30:29.572 --> 00:30:30.825
the activities,

00:30:31.352 --> 00:30:33.697
the dances, the secret meetings,

00:30:34.831 --> 00:30:35.831
the food,

00:30:36.439 --> 00:30:38.039
everything taken care of.

00:30:39.133 --> 00:30:40.388
Right? The grounds,

00:30:41.032 --> 00:30:42.250
the properties.

00:30:43.277 --> 00:30:46.050
There's no, like,
do-it-yourselfers, I'm sure.

00:30:47.542 --> 00:30:48.542
Golf,

00:30:49.040 --> 00:30:50.040
water,

00:30:50.427 --> 00:30:52.490
removed from the rest of the country,

00:30:53.985 --> 00:30:55.391
but in so many ways,

00:30:56.095 --> 00:30:58.143
having so much power in the country.

00:30:59.083 --> 00:31:00.566
Isn't it interesting how that works?

00:31:00.566 --> 00:31:03.536
A lot of the people that control
and move the levers of power

00:31:03.536 --> 00:31:04.912
are very much detached

00:31:05.650 --> 00:31:08.383
from even where we were this morning.

00:31:12.884 --> 00:31:14.939
Look at that beautiful interior.

00:31:15.657 --> 00:31:18.736
And that's not to judge,
it's just to point out a reality.

00:31:18.736 --> 00:31:20.229
They're very much isolated.

00:31:21.067 --> 00:31:24.014
And so how does
the everyday person think in America?

00:31:24.579 --> 00:31:27.279
And even that for someone
that's traveling like myself,

00:31:27.798 --> 00:31:29.003
That is complicated.

00:31:29.334 --> 00:31:31.304
You can be out at the shrimp boats,

00:31:31.991 --> 00:31:33.220
talking to those guys.

00:31:33.220 --> 00:31:35.804
All sorts of types
make this thing go around.

00:31:35.804 --> 00:31:37.004
That's the beauty of it.

00:31:37.521 --> 00:31:40.317
But to truly understand
it's a full-time job.

00:31:40.536 --> 00:31:43.027
It really is.
And then at that, I'm learning

00:31:43.730 --> 00:31:45.076
today all new territory.

00:31:45.927 --> 00:31:47.674
And it just goes on and on, guys.

00:31:47.675 --> 00:31:49.872
Look at this place. What a beauty.

00:31:50.559 --> 00:31:51.878
Hollyborne mansion.

00:31:52.765 --> 00:31:53.725
Stone home.

00:31:56.222 --> 00:31:57.222
With the brick.

00:31:57.595 --> 00:31:59.524
Oh, what's that called? I forget the term.

00:31:59.524 --> 00:32:02.469
The compacted seashell cement combo.

00:32:02.469 --> 00:32:04.962
What is that
for those that know in the comments?

00:32:04.962 --> 00:32:06.790
Look at that detail. Oh.

00:32:09.863 --> 00:32:12.005
Yeah, we're not getting in
any of these homes.

00:32:14.260 --> 00:32:16.011
See a fireplace in the back there.

00:32:17.270 --> 00:32:19.055
And the feeling here, the feeling

00:32:19.643 --> 00:32:21.808
you'd want to
go back to it for a little bit.

00:32:22.656 --> 00:32:23.397
Right?

00:32:23.398 --> 00:32:24.582
Go back to those days.

00:32:24.839 --> 00:32:28.214
I mean, very few
watching this channel have billions.

00:32:28.214 --> 00:32:29.812
Though, you'd be surprised.

00:32:30.698 --> 00:32:34.841
But for most of us, we were never in
this world of living in such wealth.

00:32:35.303 --> 00:32:37.708
But it would be cool
to step back for a little bit.

00:32:37.708 --> 00:32:39.408
See what this was like.

00:32:39.408 --> 00:32:40.996
I'm sure it was very stiff.

00:32:40.997 --> 00:32:44.360
Very little room to go outside the edges.

00:32:44.717 --> 00:32:45.717
I would think.

00:32:46.355 --> 00:32:47.949
You gotta dress a certain way.

00:32:47.949 --> 00:32:49.862
You gotta speak a certain way.

00:32:50.262 --> 00:32:52.713
I'm sure there were more just social rules

00:32:53.556 --> 00:32:55.797
for how you have to be in society.

00:32:56.610 --> 00:32:58.760
So that could be a little restrictive but,

00:32:59.543 --> 00:33:01.573
the simplicity, in a way, of

00:33:02.240 --> 00:33:06.303
not having tech, or TV,
or anything like that,

00:33:07.281 --> 00:33:10.166
A lot of relationships.
It was all relationships.

00:33:10.890 --> 00:33:11.890
[birds chirping]

00:33:12.490 --> 00:33:16.332
I guess that's also
considered one of the first

00:33:17.211 --> 00:33:21.153
condo styles in building in architecture.

00:33:32.140 --> 00:33:36.588
Here we have supposedly
where the Federal Reserve met here.

00:33:36.588 --> 00:33:38.417
They started 1910.

00:33:38.897 --> 00:33:42.064
A secret meeting of
top US financial leaders

00:33:42.064 --> 00:33:44.169
was held here at the club

00:33:44.611 --> 00:33:48.191
to draft ideas that became
a blueprint for the eventual

00:33:48.628 --> 00:33:51.128
Federal Reserve system.

00:33:51.128 --> 00:33:53.129
Nobody knew they were coming here.

00:33:53.129 --> 00:33:55.500
They had their separate train car.

00:33:55.928 --> 00:33:59.474
Six men from the elite
of the banking and financial world.

00:33:59.965 --> 00:34:00.964
1910.

00:34:01.670 --> 00:34:02.931
Let's figure out

00:34:03.999 --> 00:34:07.117
how we're going to
financially run the world.

00:34:08.198 --> 00:34:09.198
Isn't that wild?

00:34:10.176 --> 00:34:12.949
I mean the world because the US system,

00:34:13.375 --> 00:34:15.121
the Federal Reserve, determines so much

00:34:15.885 --> 00:34:18.664
how the world moves financially.

00:34:20.867 --> 00:34:22.223
Ben Bernanke was here.

00:34:23.314 --> 00:34:25.751
For these guys.
I bet these are their heroes.

00:34:28.270 --> 00:34:31.258
So during World War II
this all sort of came to an end.

00:34:31.258 --> 00:34:35.176
The state of Georgia
purchased the island in 1947

00:34:35.940 --> 00:34:38.019
and opened it to the public
as a state park.

00:34:38.413 --> 00:34:42.511
So most of this island I believe
is owned by the state of Georgia.

00:34:42.907 --> 00:34:45.554
There are also
regular citizens living here.

00:34:45.848 --> 00:34:47.250
And now we're going to cruise.

00:34:47.250 --> 00:34:49.500
See what it's like
for the people living here.

00:34:51.071 --> 00:34:54.552
I'm right across the street, guys,
looks like this.

00:34:54.552 --> 00:34:58.216
Nice residential so people
are living out here full-time.

00:34:58.730 --> 00:35:01.573
I'm sure there's some second homes,
a deer in the lawn,

00:35:03.402 --> 00:35:04.402
a couple deer.

00:35:05.019 --> 00:35:06.644
Lot of American flags.

00:35:07.308 --> 00:35:11.622
This zone is just hiring
so many people from the mainland.

00:35:11.622 --> 00:35:13.437
I think the town is Brunswick.

00:35:13.437 --> 00:35:15.980
I'm sure a lot of people
are coming over from Brunswick.

00:35:15.980 --> 00:35:17.862
That being the feeder community.

00:35:18.291 --> 00:35:21.322
And then here being
the more elite community

00:35:21.322 --> 00:35:23.979
where people are hiring out those services.

00:35:23.979 --> 00:35:26.595
A place like Jekyll
without a place like Brunswick,

00:35:26.595 --> 00:35:29.590
and I'm spitballing here.
I could be off, but I think it's Brunswick,

00:35:29.590 --> 00:35:30.706
really doesn't operate.

00:35:30.707 --> 00:35:34.348
I doubt there's much
cheap housing out here on the island.

00:35:35.227 --> 00:35:36.705
Got some cool bike paths.

00:35:36.706 --> 00:35:39.287
These streets are beautiful.

00:35:39.287 --> 00:35:41.446
Think of when the sun is filtering through.

00:35:41.843 --> 00:35:43.663
It's got to be majestic out here.

00:35:44.333 --> 00:35:46.094
Golf club. Tennis courts.

00:35:47.195 --> 00:35:50.488
There's not much here guys.
I'm sure there's some beautiful beaches.

00:35:50.931 --> 00:35:53.802
But as far as people
and life on the streets,

00:35:54.221 --> 00:35:55.383
it's a quiet place.

00:35:55.683 --> 00:35:58.065
I think that's why people are here.
They want a quiet place.

00:35:58.470 --> 00:35:59.910
A lot of older people here.

00:36:00.258 --> 00:36:02.740
I'm sure multi-generational families here.

00:36:03.328 --> 00:36:05.308
But this is what it's looking like.

00:36:05.308 --> 00:36:08.249
And it goes a bit more north.

00:36:08.249 --> 00:36:12.597
Just this residential
and then sort of just goes to nature.

00:36:12.603 --> 00:36:14.292
So what are we looking at?

00:36:14.633 --> 00:36:16.002
Pretty much that.

00:36:16.205 --> 00:36:18.555
We started over there.
There's a little airport.

00:36:19.093 --> 00:36:20.143
That's where we were.

00:36:20.699 --> 00:36:22.490
And we're going up here.

00:36:22.490 --> 00:36:24.446
We'll turn around,
go back to the south part.

00:36:24.446 --> 00:36:26.201
But first impressions,

00:36:26.577 --> 00:36:30.121
calm, nice, wealthy, orderly type of place.

00:36:31.766 --> 00:36:33.916
Looks like they're redoing this place here.

00:36:35.179 --> 00:36:37.020
-How's it going man?
-Hello, sir.

00:36:37.020 --> 00:36:38.070
How's the work going?

00:36:38.780 --> 00:36:41.215
-Here?
-Yeah. Busy? Lots of work?

00:36:42.011 --> 00:36:43.630
-[Spanish]
-Yeah.

00:36:43.630 --> 00:36:45.970
You guys live in Brunswick
or you live here?

00:36:45.970 --> 00:36:47.248
Live in Brunswick.

00:36:47.650 --> 00:36:50.080
Okay, so most people work here.
They live in Brunswick.

00:36:50.732 --> 00:36:52.398
-They come here, work, go home.
-Yeah.

00:36:53.480 --> 00:36:55.186
This is the hub.

00:36:55.793 --> 00:36:58.349
The center point of Jekyll Island.

00:36:59.265 --> 00:37:00.590
Beach Village.

00:37:00.590 --> 00:37:02.314
This is where it all happens.

00:37:02.314 --> 00:37:04.815
You want your nightlife.
You want your t-shirts.

00:37:05.445 --> 00:37:06.445
That's about it.

00:37:07.281 --> 00:37:09.117
Okay. I think we've seen enough.

00:37:09.651 --> 00:37:13.423
Let's go to our last island, San Simons.

00:37:14.229 --> 00:37:18.201
You can see at this time of day
all the workers coming off the island.

00:37:18.552 --> 00:37:20.686
Back to Brunswick or wherever here.

00:37:20.687 --> 00:37:22.037
We got the bridge up ahead.

00:37:22.616 --> 00:37:25.704
San Simons, the biggest
of the islands today.

00:37:25.704 --> 00:37:27.277
The most people also.

00:37:27.277 --> 00:37:30.518
Roughly 15,000 people live on the island.

00:37:31.082 --> 00:37:33.469
And you're also getting
second home snowbirds.

00:37:33.469 --> 00:37:35.919
So that, I'm sure,
knocks up the population a bit.

00:37:36.355 --> 00:37:37.355
[country music]

00:37:50.844 --> 00:37:55.360
You know, St. Simons has
a little bit of a Hamptons feel to it.

00:37:55.360 --> 00:37:57.220
Southern Hamptons.

00:37:57.680 --> 00:37:59.894
You got everything you need here as far as

00:37:59.894 --> 00:38:03.500
restaurants, grocery stores,
hardware shops, bicycle shops.

00:38:03.500 --> 00:38:05.987
You know, it looks pretty active
and tourist friendly.

00:38:05.987 --> 00:38:08.169
I'm sure it gets super busy out here.

00:38:08.931 --> 00:38:11.046
Let's check out
one of these roads off the main drag.

00:38:12.378 --> 00:38:14.226
This is really nice out here.

00:38:14.978 --> 00:38:16.461
It's just the trees make it.

00:38:17.102 --> 00:38:19.544
And they put the tree
right in the middle of the road.

00:38:20.459 --> 00:38:21.834
Wow, this is beautiful.

00:38:22.440 --> 00:38:24.677
Yeah, Southern Hamptons feel.

00:38:25.331 --> 00:38:28.975
I haven't seen the mega plots
with the huge hedges and that stuff.

00:38:28.975 --> 00:38:32.947
But like your average Hamptons
neighborhood sort of feels like this.

00:38:33.759 --> 00:38:36.334
And then the swamp comes right in,
Georgia style.

00:38:37.153 --> 00:38:39.053
Things just really well taken care of.

00:38:40.176 --> 00:38:42.152
There's something about
living on an island.

00:38:42.152 --> 00:38:45.358
You're so close to so much stuff here.

00:38:45.358 --> 00:38:48.901
Brunswick right over the water,
but then that divide, that moat,

00:38:48.901 --> 00:38:51.921
really changes the whole feel of the place.

00:38:53.139 --> 00:38:55.000
Here we go, right up to the water.

00:38:57.200 --> 00:38:59.550
Here's the first person
I've seen out and about.

00:39:01.580 --> 00:39:02.580
How you doing, sir?

00:39:03.364 --> 00:39:05.658
It's so convenient.

00:39:06.289 --> 00:39:08.590
-Living over here?
-Living over here.

00:39:08.590 --> 00:39:11.388
You're half a mile from the post office.

00:39:12.020 --> 00:39:15.970
Winn-Dixie, Harris Theater,
half a mile that way.

00:39:16.179 --> 00:39:17.550
-You got it all.
-Yeah.

00:39:17.550 --> 00:39:19.090
For somebody my age,

00:39:20.176 --> 00:39:22.558
forgive me for going into my sales pitch,

00:39:22.559 --> 00:39:25.183
but our house is on the market right now.

00:39:25.183 --> 00:39:26.200
-You're moving.

00:39:26.200 --> 00:39:32.366
My wife, we need to be back to Colorado
where we get support from family.

00:39:32.840 --> 00:39:35.020
Okay, so I'm going to show your house, 219?

00:39:35.320 --> 00:39:36.413
Five Pounds Road.

00:39:36.413 --> 00:39:38.880
-If there weren't health issues,
would you want to stay?

00:39:38.880 --> 00:39:40.450
Oh, absolutely.

00:39:40.451 --> 00:39:42.200
This is a fantastic place.

00:39:42.200 --> 00:39:44.066
-What's the vibe out here? What's it like?

00:39:44.920 --> 00:39:47.527
You could find almost any vibe,

00:39:47.528 --> 00:39:51.921
but it's especially nice for retired folks.

00:39:51.921 --> 00:39:52.921
-Okay.
-Yeah.

00:39:52.921 --> 00:39:55.030
Are there younger families here or no?

00:39:55.030 --> 00:39:58.817
Oh, yes.
Yeah, a lot of them. Right on this street.

00:39:58.817 --> 00:39:59.817
-Okay.
-Lots of kids.

00:40:02.704 --> 00:40:03.817
-[child] Hello.
-Hello.

00:40:06.441 --> 00:40:08.604
All right, here we go. Here's Bill's house

00:40:09.197 --> 00:40:12.072
on Zillow, $975,000.

00:40:12.480 --> 00:40:14.215
So that's what it costs here.

00:40:14.215 --> 00:40:16.593
Has to leave because of medical reasons.

00:40:16.909 --> 00:40:17.909
Loves it here.

00:40:18.870 --> 00:40:19.870
There you go.

00:40:21.290 --> 00:40:24.033
That's beautiful,
the house on the other side of that pond.

00:40:24.775 --> 00:40:26.490
-How you doing, man?
-Good. How are you?

00:40:26.490 --> 00:40:29.380
Good. I'm making a video of the area.
Can I ask you a question?

00:40:29.380 --> 00:40:30.519
-Yeah.
How is it?

00:40:31.511 --> 00:40:32.959
-I love it.
-You love it?

00:40:32.959 --> 00:40:34.970
-Yeah.
-Are there many kids your age out here?

00:40:34.970 --> 00:40:36.678
There's a good bit, yes, sir.

00:40:36.679 --> 00:40:38.500
We all like ride bikes and stuff.

00:40:38.500 --> 00:40:39.500
-You do, huh?

00:40:39.500 --> 00:40:40.950
It's how we get around.

00:40:40.950 --> 00:40:43.168
-You got a cool thing going out here.
-Yes, sir.

00:40:43.168 --> 00:40:47.318
Where do I gotta go? If I'm here for like
literally another hour, where should I go?

00:40:47.668 --> 00:40:48.701
Um…

00:40:49.460 --> 00:40:52.828
Probably go to like a Marina
or something to watch the sunset.

00:40:53.150 --> 00:40:56.371
-Go to a Marina. You're in high school?
-I'm a freshman, yes, sir.

00:40:56.371 --> 00:40:58.872
-You go to high school here? Nice.
-I go to Glynn Academy.

00:40:58.872 --> 00:41:00.023
-Yes, sir.
-Yeah.

00:41:00.023 --> 00:41:02.265
-I love this, sir. That's awesome.
-Yes, sir. Thank you.

00:41:02.265 --> 00:41:03.284
-Take care.
-You too.

00:41:05.320 --> 00:41:06.684
Well put together, kid.

00:41:07.157 --> 00:41:08.675
Just a lot of smiles here.

00:41:08.675 --> 00:41:11.643
I didn't put the camera
'cause the family was in the lawn

00:41:11.643 --> 00:41:14.493
and they had their little kids
and I gotta be really careful about that.

00:41:14.493 --> 00:41:16.353
All smiles, all waves.

00:41:17.202 --> 00:41:19.418
Just really pleasant out here.

00:41:20.023 --> 00:41:22.153
You know, sometimes
when you go into a neighborhood,

00:41:22.153 --> 00:41:23.803
you have the out-of-state plates,

00:41:24.504 --> 00:41:27.778
This is a rental car
with North Carolina plates.

00:41:27.778 --> 00:41:29.479
They know you're not living here.

00:41:30.196 --> 00:41:31.146
There's a coldness.

00:41:32.093 --> 00:41:33.154
Not here.

00:41:33.154 --> 00:41:35.617
They open up and wave,

00:41:36.365 --> 00:41:37.365
and want to talk.

00:41:38.137 --> 00:41:39.474
Really nice.

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:43.423
I want to show you guys
there's an island off of here.

00:41:43.760 --> 00:41:44.760
Totally private.

00:41:45.023 --> 00:41:46.596
Like Jekyll used to be.

00:41:47.141 --> 00:41:48.663
Modern-day Jekyll Island.

00:41:50.202 --> 00:41:52.304
I don't know if the camera's
picking it up here,

00:41:52.304 --> 00:41:54.685
but there are a bunch of jets out there.

00:41:54.685 --> 00:41:56.955
Maybe 10, 15 on the tarmac.

00:41:57.219 --> 00:41:59.141
They've got their own private airport here.

00:42:00.129 --> 00:42:03.067
All right, we're coming up on Sea Island.

00:42:03.067 --> 00:42:05.295
All the way up the coastline there.

00:42:05.939 --> 00:42:08.225
Members and property owners only.

00:42:08.225 --> 00:42:09.925
We're not gonna be able to get on.

00:42:10.783 --> 00:42:14.097
Let's just try for the fun of it. It's not
gonna happen, but we'll give it a go.

00:42:15.446 --> 00:42:17.406
-How you doing, ma'am?
-[woman] Hello.

00:42:17.406 --> 00:42:19.239
There's no way I can cruise on here?

00:42:19.240 --> 00:42:21.258
No, it's all private from here on back.

00:42:21.258 --> 00:42:25.260
Unless you're a member or a guest
at the cloister or live on property.

00:42:25.260 --> 00:42:27.401
-Okay. How many people live out here?

00:42:27.401 --> 00:42:29.157
-It's 15 miles of beach.
-Wow.

00:42:29.158 --> 00:42:30.646
So we've got quite a bit.

00:42:31.017 --> 00:42:33.643
-That's cool. Is it beautiful?
-It is pretty.

00:42:34.669 --> 00:42:37.061
And I wish I could let you go
so you can show it.

00:42:37.357 --> 00:42:39.789
-I know. You seem very nice.
-Yeah.

00:42:39.790 --> 00:42:41.752
-But we're not going to do it.
-I just can't.

00:42:41.752 --> 00:42:44.385
Yeah. Is St Simons poorer
compared to this?

00:42:45.058 --> 00:42:46.967
You know, I don't know.

00:42:47.268 --> 00:42:49.320
'Cause I'm from Jacksonville, Florida.

00:42:49.320 --> 00:42:50.623
-Jax. Nice, good…

00:42:50.623 --> 00:42:53.270
-I'm just in awe
by this being this close to the beach.

00:42:53.270 --> 00:42:54.538
Have you been out here?

00:42:54.928 --> 00:42:56.260
Yeah. It is so pretty.

00:42:56.260 --> 00:42:58.543
-Super wealthy.
-Right. Oh yeah.

00:42:58.544 --> 00:43:02.262
I haven't questioned it but I know
people spend thousands of dollars to rent.

00:43:02.263 --> 00:43:06.560
I think it's like $15,000 to $20,000
a night for the cottages.

00:43:06.560 --> 00:43:09.013
-Oh wow. $15,000 to $20,000 a night?
-A night.

00:43:09.244 --> 00:43:10.266
-A night.
-A night.

00:43:10.534 --> 00:43:12.070
-For the cottage.
-For the cottages.

00:43:12.070 --> 00:43:13.730
Wow. Okay.

00:43:13.731 --> 00:43:15.457
Thank you so much. Should I just turn here?

00:43:15.457 --> 00:43:19.055
Yes sir, if you go up here to the left
it'll take you back around.

00:43:19.055 --> 00:43:21.156
-Okay. Thank you.
-Thank you. Have a good evening.

00:43:21.156 --> 00:43:22.165
You too.

00:43:22.166 --> 00:43:24.164
So that's as close as we're getting guys.

00:43:24.758 --> 00:43:28.046
She said $15,000 to $20,000 a night

00:43:28.868 --> 00:43:30.470
for one of the cottages.

00:43:30.471 --> 00:43:33.540
And I'm going to drop
up on the screen right now

00:43:33.540 --> 00:43:34.430
Zillow listings.

00:43:34.431 --> 00:43:37.064
You can't Google street view this place,

00:43:37.396 --> 00:43:40.245
but I'm going to put the Zillow listings
so you can get an understanding

00:43:40.245 --> 00:43:43.227
of what the prices are for homes out there.

00:43:43.942 --> 00:43:45.632
Who knew Georgia had so much money?

00:43:45.633 --> 00:43:48.264
I mean Georgians did
or people in the South did,

00:43:48.264 --> 00:43:53.432
but I had no clue that
there were these serious wealthy enclaves

00:43:53.929 --> 00:43:56.604
on these islands in the state.

00:44:00.860 --> 00:44:03.357
All right guys,
end of the road here, St. Simons.

00:44:03.357 --> 00:44:05.443
We hardly touched it. Ran out of light.

00:44:05.716 --> 00:44:07.770
It's a big island.
There's a lot going on here.

00:44:08.114 --> 00:44:12.642
And I gotta say, I got caught up on Tybee
this morning with Jacqueline.

00:44:12.642 --> 00:44:14.269
That was so much fun with her

00:44:14.269 --> 00:44:16.264
that it sort of threw everything behind.

00:44:16.264 --> 00:44:19.225
My fault because I was just
enjoying myself so much.

00:44:19.225 --> 00:44:20.890
The last island here, St. Simons.

00:44:21.507 --> 00:44:22.636
Hardly saw it.

00:44:22.636 --> 00:44:24.323
So sorry to those locals.

00:44:24.910 --> 00:44:26.526
But it's interesting, right?

00:44:26.526 --> 00:44:30.111
Tybee, you have that
what felt like a real deep community,

00:44:30.863 --> 00:44:32.759
real local vibe to it,

00:44:33.178 --> 00:44:34.978
to Jekyll, the old world.

00:44:35.251 --> 00:44:37.132
And then here, this is a place where

00:44:37.450 --> 00:44:41.644
drove by high schools, grammar schools,
basketball hoops, kids playing.

00:44:41.644 --> 00:44:43.810
It's more of a, I'd say,

00:44:43.810 --> 00:44:46.056
more of a family type place

00:44:46.056 --> 00:44:48.503
sprinkled in with tourists, snowbirds,

00:44:48.982 --> 00:44:50.332
and second homes, I'm sure.

00:44:50.940 --> 00:44:53.219
But three islands, three different worlds.

00:44:53.685 --> 00:44:55.960
Thanks for coming on that journey,
you guys.

00:44:55.960 --> 00:44:56.960
Until the next one.

00:44:58.503 --> 00:44:59.503
[country music]

